# Relic Tier List and Strategy

## S-Tier Relics (Always Take)

### Snecko Eye
- Effect: Draw 2 additional cards each turn. Randomize card costs (0-3).
- Why it is S-tier: The extra draw is enormous. On average, costs stay the same, but you now see 7 cards per turn instead of 5. High-cost cards become amazing because they frequently cost 0-1.
- Best with: Expensive cards like Demon Form, Bludgeon, Carnage. Terrible with 0-cost decks.

### Dead Branch
- Effect: Whenever you exhaust a card, add a random card to your hand.
- Why it is S-tier: Combined with Corruption (all skills cost 0, exhaust), you generate endless free cards every turn. Even without Corruption, any exhaust-heavy deck becomes incredibly powerful.

### Runic Pyramid
- Effect: No longer discard hand at end of turn.
- Why it is S-tier: Lets you save key cards for the right moment. Dramatically improves consistency. Combo pieces are always available when you need them.
- Downside: Hand can clog with Curses or Wounds. Need some exhaust to manage hand size.

## A-Tier Relics (Almost Always Take)

### Vajra
- Effect: Start every combat with +1 Strength.
- Why it is A-tier: Free permanent damage boost. Every attack benefits. Simple and universally good on Ironclad.

### Bag of Preparation
- Effect: Draw 2 additional cards on turn 1.
- Why it is A-tier: Turn 1 is often the most important turn. Seeing 7 cards on turn 1 dramatically improves your opening.

### Pen Nib
- Effect: Every 10th attack deals double damage.
- Why it is A-tier: Pairs excellently with heavy hitters like Heavy Blade or Bludgeon. Track the counter and time your big attacks.

### Anchor
- Effect: Start every combat with 10 block.
- Why it is A-tier: Free defense on turn 1 lets you play aggressively. Particularly good against Act 1 elites.

## B-Tier Relics (Situationally Good)

### Ornamental Fan
- Effect: Every 3rd attack played, gain 4 block.
- Why: Good in decks that play many small attacks per turn. Less useful in big-hit decks.

### Kunai
- Effect: Every 3rd attack played, gain +1 Dexterity.
- Why: Scaling defense through attacks. Excellent in shiv-style or multi-attack decks.

### Molten Egg
- Effect: All attack cards obtained are upgraded.
- Why: Saves precious campfire upgrades. More impactful in Act 1 when many cards are still being drafted.

## Relics to Avoid

### Ectoplasm
- Effect: Gain 1 energy but can no longer gain gold.
- Why to avoid: Gold buys shop relics, card removals, and potions. Losing gold income cripples your run long-term unless you are already in Act 3.

### Philosophy Stone
- Effect: Gain 1 energy but all enemies start with 1 Strength.
- Why to avoid: The enemy strength compounds over multi-turn fights. Boss fights become significantly harder.